# Changelog - xcesppkg

## 0.1.63

- **Route-based IPsec (XFRM interface) tunnel mode.**  Third IPsec data-plane
  mode alongside the existing transport and tunnel-policy modes.  Creates
  a Linux XFRM netdev (kernel ≥4.19) joined to a strongSwan SA via a
  deterministic if-id; packets routed through the device get
  ESP-encapsulated by the SA.  Operator surface:
  ```
  interface tun-hub
    type xfrm
    xfrm
      ipsec-conn HUB
    !
    address 10.99.0.1/30
  !
  ipsec
    connection HUB
      ...
  ```
  Both ends use the same `ipsec-conn` name; the mapper hashes that name
  to allocate a matching if-id on both sides.  Operators who need
  asymmetric or peer-interop control can set `if-id` on the xfrm block
  and `if-id-in`/`if-id-out` on the children explicitly.  Co-exists with
  X.509 (Ch06) and PSK (Ch03/Ch05) on the same router
- Per-namespace `charon-ns.conf` now disables the `bypass-lan` plugin
  (mirrors the host's `load = no` in
  /etc/strongswan/strongswan.d/charon/bypass-lan.conf).  Without this,
  per-namespace charon auto-installed catch-all PASS shunt policies for
  every local subnet, which preempted wildcard-TS SAs used by route-
  based IPsec
- `swanctl --load-all` now runs with `SWANCTL_DIR` set even in the
  default namespace.  Previously the host-side `swanctl` reload
  defaulted to the distro template directory
  (`/etc/strongswan/swanctl/conf.d/` on Fedora) and silently skipped
  loading the connections xcespproc had just written
- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.24, xcespcli 0.1.16, xcespproc 0.1.25,
  xcespwdog 0.1.1, xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.153, xcesp-on-pw 0.0.2,
  xcesp-on-xc 0.0.2, xcespmap 0.1.1, xcespschema 0.1.1,
  xcespconfig 0.1.1, xcesppy 0.0.4

## 0.1.62

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.23, xcespcli 0.1.16, xcespproc 0.1.24,
  xcespwdog 0.1.1 (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.149).  Three big security
  features ship together:
  - **Encrypted IPsec PSKs at rest.**  Plaintext PSKs typed into
    `ipsec / secret <NAME> / secret <plaintext>` are replaced on
    commit with `${enc:v1:<base64>}`.  `show running` and saved
    `xcespserver.conf` now contain only the encrypted form.
    Reversible AES-256-CBC + PBKDF2 keyed off `/etc/machine-id`
    (device-bound; restoring a backup to a different machine
    forces the operator to re-enter — see notes).
  - **X.509 certificate management.**  New CLI verbs:
    `certificate ca-import / import / delete / generate-key /
    generate-csr`, `show certificate`.  PEM blobs are pasted via a
    heredoc input mode (sentinel = `END`).  Material lives in
    `/var/xcesp/dsk/cert/{ca,dev,key}/` with restricted perms
    (`0750` dirs, `0640` files, `root:xcesp`).
  - **IPsec X.509 auth.**  Two new schema attrs:
    `ipsec-local.cert <NAME>` and `ipsec-remote.ca-cert
    <NAME>[,<NAME>...]`.  Mapper auto-emits `auth = pubkey`,
    `certs = /…/dev/<NAME>.pem`, `cacerts = /…/ca/<NAME>.pem`, and
    a `private-<NAME> { file = /…/key/<NAME>.key }` stanza so
    `swanctl --load-all` picks up everything in one shot.
- `install.sh` provisions `dsk/cert/{ca,dev,key}` on fresh installs.
  Pre-0.1.62 upgrades need a one-time manual create (or a re-run of
  install.sh).

## 0.1.61

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.22, xcespcli 0.1.15, xcespproc 0.1.23,
  xcespwdog 0.1.1 (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.148).  `arp-table-size` moved
  from VRF to router level — the Linux neighbour cache is one-per-
  netns, not per-VRF, so the previous placement was misleading.
- **Migration note**: configs using `router/<R>/vrf/<V>/arp-table-size
  <N>` will be rejected with "unknown attribute 'arp-table-size'" on
  the next commit.  Move the attribute one level up to
  `router/<R>/arp-table-size <N>` and re-commit.

## 0.1.60

- Doc-httpd not starting after install (production-only bug).  Root
  cause: in xcesppkg, the wdog process list at
  `/run/xcesp/xcespwdog_proc.ini` is generated by **xcesp-activate**
  (bash, run via systemd `ExecStartPre=+`), not by xcespserver's C++
  `WdogConfigWriter`.  The 0.1.57 doc-httpd emission landed only in
  the C++ writer that xcesptest consumes — production never saw it.
- Fix in `xcesp-activate`:
  1. Read `[DOC_HTTPD]` from `xcespserver.ini` (POSIX-portable awk
     parser; tolerates `; ... ` and `# ...` inline comments).
  2. When `ENABLED=true` and `DOC_DIR` exists, append a
     `[process.N+1]` block to `xcespwdog_proc.ini` launching
     `python3 -m http.server --bind <addr> --directory <dir> <port>`
     with heartbeat polling disabled and respawn on.
  3. Idempotently inject the `[DOC_HTTPD]` defaults stanza into an
     existing `xcespserver.ini` that predates the feature (same
     pattern as the older `PROC_CONFIG_FILE` injection), so the
     operator can see and edit the tunables in the usual place.
- The on-disk xcesp-activate script self-refreshes from
  `/var/xcesp/mainsw/scripts/` on every service start, so once 0.1.60
  is installed the new logic takes effect at the next
  `systemctl restart xcesp` — no manual edit required.
- Bundled binaries unchanged from 0.1.59 (xcespserver 0.1.22,
  xcespcli 0.1.15, xcespproc 0.1.22, xcespwdog 0.1.1,
  xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.147).

## 0.1.59

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.22, xcespcli 0.1.15, xcespproc 0.1.22,
  xcespwdog 0.1.1 (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.147).  CLI fix: `show status` /
  `show running` / `show event` returned nothing when the CLI was
  navigated into a deep path (~30 chars or longer).  Cause was the
  prompt-display path truncation leaking into the server query body;
  introduced a separate `currentFullPathStr()` helper for protocol
  bodies and pointed all six show-command call sites at it.  Pure
  client-side; the on-device xcespserver / xcespproc binaries can stay
  on 0.1.22 / 0.0.147.

## 0.1.58

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.22, xcespcli 0.1.14, xcespproc 0.1.22,
  xcespwdog 0.1.1 (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.147).  Adds the per-interface
  `mtu <N>` attribute (integer 68..12000, clamp-and-warn against the
  device's kernel-reported max/min).  Applies to every interface type.
  `show status` reflects the **actual** kernel MTU — the value after
  any clamp — under `router/<rtr>/vrf/<vrf>/interface/<name>/mtu`.

## 0.1.57

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.22, xcespcli 0.1.14, xcespproc 0.1.21,
  xcespwdog 0.1.1 (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.146).  Adds a built-in user-manual
  HTTP server, supervised by xcespwdog:
  - The mkdocs-built static site (`doc/site/`) is bundled into the
    package under `doc/` and installed to `/var/xcesp/doc/`.
  - `cfg/xcespserver.ini` gains a `[DOC_HTTPD]` section
    (`ENABLED=true`, `BIND_ADDR=0.0.0.0`, `PORT=8080`,
    `DOC_DIR=/var/xcesp/doc`).
  - xcespserver emits an extra `[process.N]` block into
    `xcespwdog_gen.ini` so xcespwdog launches and respawns
    `python3 -m http.server` autonomously.  The docs stay up while
    xcespserver restarts.
  - Bundling is conditional: if the build host's `../doc/site/` is
    absent the doc tree is skipped (package still builds; the
    `[DOC_HTTPD]` block is a no-op when DOC_DIR is empty).
  - **Note on default bind**: `0.0.0.0` is intentional for the INI-only
    phase.  A future schema-driven `doc-server` block will flip the
    default to `127.0.0.1` and make LAN exposure an explicit opt-in.

## 0.1.56

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.21, xcespcli 0.1.14, xcespproc 0.1.21,
  xcespwdog 0.1.1 (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.146).  New `traceroute` CLI
  command:
  ```
  traceroute ADDRESS [source ADDR] [router ROUTER] [vrf VRF]
             [max-hops N] [protocol udp|tcp|icmp] [port N]
  ```
  Mirrors `ping`: same CLI_ACTION_EXEC wire path, same PTY streaming
  back to the operator, same ambient-CAP_NET_RAW delegation in the
  forked child.  `-n` (no-DNS) is hardcoded in the wrapper.  VRF
  binding uses `-i <vrf-master>`, source via `-s`.

## 0.1.55

- Rolls forward to xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.145 — schema-only fix in
  `router.validate.py` that stops rejecting valid `access-list-l4`
  configs where `protocol = any` (or `icmp`) is combined with
  `src-port` / `dst-port`.  Binaries unchanged from 0.1.54
  (xcespserver 0.1.21 / xcespcli 0.1.13 / xcespproc 0.1.20 /
  xcespwdog 0.1.1).

## 0.1.54

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.21, xcespcli 0.1.13, xcespproc 0.1.20,
  xcespwdog 0.1.1 (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.144).  Adds two new interface
  filter capabilities:
  - **L4 port filtering** via the new `access-list-l4` ACL type
    (protocol tcp/udp/icmp/any + src/dst CIDR + src-port/dst-port).
    Reuses the existing `ingress-filter` / `egress-filter` interface
    attrs.
  - **MAC ingress filter** via the new `mac-acl` ACL type and
    interface attrs `mac-ingress-filter` /
    `mac-ingress-filter-default`.  Whitelist = permit+deny, blacklist
    = deny+permit.  Egress not offered (router's own MAC is the
    egress source).
- Also includes the `tar -m` fix in xcespserver so this and future
  upgrades extract correctly on devices whose RTC is behind the
  build-host clock (no NTP).  Existing operators upgrading from
  0.1.51/0.1.52 with stale clocks must either fix the clock or extract
  manually with `tar xzmf` once — after 0.1.54 is in place the issue
  is gone for good.
- Verified end-to-end: xcespqa Ch14 (IP filter) still 9/9 PASS;
  Ch15 (L4 ports) + Ch16 (MAC ACL) added under ON-RTR-STATIC.

## 0.1.53

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.20, xcespcli 0.1.13, xcespproc 0.1.19,
  xcespwdog 0.1.1 (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.143).  Same interface ACL filter
  feature as 0.1.52, plus the L3MDEV fix: for non-default VRFs the
  ingress/egress filter now installs an additional INPUT/OUTPUT hook on
  the VRF master device, so locally-destined ICMP/UDP/TCP traffic
  (rewritten past the slave device by L3MDEV on kernels with
  `raw_l3mdev_accept=1`) is correctly subject to the ACL.  Verified
  end-to-end by xcespqa Ch14 (9/9 PASS)

## 0.1.52

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.20, xcespcli 0.1.13, xcespproc 0.1.18,
  xcespwdog 0.1.1 (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.142).  Adds the ACL-based
  per-interface ingress/egress filter feature: four new interface
  attrs (`ingress-filter`, `ingress-filter-default`, `egress-filter`,
  `egress-filter-default`) translate router-scope access-list /
  access-list-extended definitions into Linux iptables filter chains
  hooked into INPUT/FORWARD (ingress) and OUTPUT/FORWARD (egress).
  Works in default and non-default VRFs.  No CLI changes required —
  config-tree commands are schema-driven

## 0.1.51

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.20, xcespcli 0.1.13, xcespproc 0.1.17,
  xcespwdog 0.1.1 (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.141).  Rolls 0.1.50 forward with
  the streaming-cancel SIGKILL fallback in xcespserver 0.1.20 — so
  Ctrl-C on a stuck transfer (firewall silently dropping, network
  black-hole, etc.) can never re-block xcespserver

## 0.1.50

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.19, xcespcli 0.1.13, xcespproc 0.1.17,
  xcespwdog 0.1.1 (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.141).  `copy ... scp://` is now
  a streaming action — xcespserver runs scp via a PTY in a child
  process and forwards the progress bar to the CLI in real time, so
  the event loop stays responsive even on slow ARM64 / LTE links.
  Fixes the regression on ARM64 where every large-file transfer
  drowned all client connections via heartbeat timeout (the
  symptom that prompted this design)

## 0.1.49

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.18, xcespcli 0.1.12, xcespproc 0.1.17,
  xcespwdog 0.1.1 (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.141).  `show server` gains a
  `Software` section showing whether this is an XCESPPKG install,
  the running mainsw version, and the staged backupsw version.
  Fills the gap noted after the first end-to-end CLI upgrade test
  — operators no longer need filesystem access to confirm what
  upgrade landed and what's queued for the next swap

## 0.1.48

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.17, xcespcli 0.1.11, xcespproc 0.1.17,
  xcespwdog 0.1.1 (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.141).  xcespserver 0.1.17 fixes
  `show ssh ...` / `clear ssh ...` / `ssh-key ...` failing with
  `error: missing ROUTER parameter` — the new SSH actions weren't
  in the local-action allowlist in `XCespCtrlServer::relayActionExec`,
  so the dispatcher tried to route them to a per-router xcespproc

## 0.1.47

- CLI upgrade is now self-sufficient.  `xcesp-activate` (the
  systemd `ExecStartPre=+` hook that runs as root) now also:
  - **Self-updates** `/usr/bin/xcesp-activate` and
    `/usr/bin/xcesp-swap.sh` from `$MAINSW/scripts/` whenever they
    differ.  Without this, a CLI swap left the old activate script
    in place forever and never picked up new install-time fixes
  - **Enforces directory perms** on `/var/xcesp`, `mainsw`,
    `backupsw` (mode 2775, group `xcesp`) — the same enforcement
    install.sh does, so a customer who only upgrades via CLI gets
    the 0.1.46 perms fix automatically on next boot
- `install.sh`: also installs the management scripts under
  `$MAINSW_DIR/scripts/` (in addition to `/usr/bin/`) so a CLI
  swap brings them along.

  **One-time bootstrap for existing 0.1.45 / 0.1.46 customers**:
  the OLD `xcesp-activate` doesn't know about self-update, so
  the first hop must still run `sudo bash install.sh` from the
  0.1.47 tarball.  After that, every subsequent upgrade flows
  through the CLI without manual steps

## 0.1.46

- `install.sh`: give the `xcesp` group write permission on
  `/var/xcesp/`, `mainsw/`, and `backupsw/` (mode 2775 with
  setgid).  Without these `copy sw <url> backup-sw` failed at
  extraction time with `tar: bin: Cannot mkdir: Permission denied`,
  and `software-install` (which renames `mainsw <-> backupsw`) needed
  root.  Files inside still stay root-owned; only the directory
  permissions change.  Bundles same binaries as 0.1.45 (xcespserver
  0.1.16, xcespcli 0.1.11, xcespproc 0.1.17, xcespwdog 0.1.1)

## 0.1.45

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.16, xcespcli 0.1.11, xcespproc 0.1.17,
  xcespwdog 0.1.1 (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.141).  Six new SSH key management
  commands let operators audit and manage xcespserver's outbound SSH
  state without root:
  - `show ssh known-hosts`        — list TOFU-trusted host keys
  - `show ssh identity`           — print xcespserver's outbound pubkey
  - `clear ssh known-host <host>` — drop a stale entry (recover from
                                    legitimate host-key rotation)
  - `clear ssh known-hosts`       — wipe all
  - `ssh-key generate [type T]`   — create xcespserver's identity
                                    (ed25519 default)
  - `ssh-key push scp://user@host` — install our pubkey on the remote
                                     `~/.ssh/authorized_keys`
  After `ssh-key push` runs once for a host, subsequent
  `copy ... scp://host/...` transfers run keyless — no password and no
  `sshpass` required.  Full TAB / `?` completion for every level

## 0.1.44

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.15, xcespcli 0.1.10, xcespproc 0.1.17,
  xcespwdog 0.1.1 (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.141).  xcespserver 0.1.15 makes
  `copy ... scp://host/path` home-relative on the remote (matching
  what operators typically mean), with `scp://host//path` reserved
  for absolute root-relative paths

## 0.1.43

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.14, xcespcli 0.1.10, xcespproc 0.1.17,
  xcespwdog 0.1.1 (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.141).  xcespserver 0.1.14 moves
  the TOFU `known_hosts` from `<DSK_DIR>/known_hosts` (root-owned
  parent, not writable by the unprivileged `xcesp` user) to the
  running user's `$HOME/.ssh/known_hosts`.  Fixes
  `Failed to add the host to the list of known hosts` on SCP/SFTP
  uploads in 0.1.41 / 0.1.42

## 0.1.42

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.13, xcespcli 0.1.10, xcespproc 0.1.17,
  xcespwdog 0.1.1 (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.141).  xcespserver 0.1.13 drops
  the process-lifetime cache in `sshpassAvailable()` — previously,
  installing `sshpass` after xcespserver was already running had no
  effect until the next restart because the negative result was
  cached.  Now we re-check on every copy via `access(X_OK)` on
  standard paths

## 0.1.41

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.12, xcespcli 0.1.10, xcespproc 0.1.17,
  xcespwdog 0.1.1 (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.141).  xcespserver 0.1.12 hardens
  the `copy ... scp://` / `sftp://` host-key handling: replaces the
  permissive `StrictHostKeyChecking=no` with TOFU
  (`StrictHostKeyChecking=accept-new` + dedicated
  `<DSK_DIR>/known_hosts`).  First contact records the key; later
  connections to the same host with a *different* key are rejected
  with the standard OpenSSH MITM warning

## 0.1.40

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.11, xcespcli 0.1.10, xcespproc 0.1.17,
  xcespwdog 0.1.1 (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.141).  Two `copy` UX fixes:
  - **xcespcli**: `TAB` / `?` after `copy` and `delete` now actually
    list the four directory categories and follow up with
    context-aware source / destination candidates (the previous
    handlers had an off-by-one that made the lists unreachable)
  - **xcespserver**: `copy ... scp://` / `sftp://` returns a clear
    error when `sshpass` isn't installed instead of leaking
    `sh: 1: sshpass: not found`; with no password, falls back to
    `BatchMode=yes` so SSH key-auth either works or fails fast

## 0.1.39

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.10, xcespcli 0.1.9, xcespproc 0.1.17, xcespwdog
  0.1.1 (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.141).  Completes the audit-and-flip of every
  FRR-default-enabled BGP boolean so that writing `no <attr>` actually
  emits the corresponding `no <FRR command>` line.  11 additional knobs
  fixed:
  - **bgp-params**: `enforce-first-as`, `suppress-duplicates`,
    `hard-administrative-reset`, `graceful-restart-notification`,
    `fast-external-failover`, `network-import-check`
  - **neighbor / group**: `enforce-first-as`, `capability-fqdn`,
    `send-community-extended`, `send-community-standard`,
    `send-community-large`

## 0.1.38

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.10, xcespcli 0.1.9, xcespproc 0.1.16, xcespwdog
  0.1.1 (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.140).  Same-shape fix as 0.1.37 but for the
  other "FRR-default-enabled" boolean: `bgp-params / no
  ebgp-requires-policy` was silently dropped because the schema had two
  redundant attrs (`ebgp-requires-policy` + `no-ebgp-requires-policy`)
  both defaulting to false-and-emit-on-true.  Schema and writer now
  consolidate to a single `ebgp-requires-policy` attr defaulting to
  `true` (mirroring FRR); writing `no ebgp-requires-policy` emits the
  explicit `no bgp ebgp-requires-policy` line.  Configs that used the
  old `no-ebgp-requires-policy true` form must switch to
  `no ebgp-requires-policy`

## 0.1.37

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.10, xcespcli 0.1.9, xcespproc 0.1.15, xcespwdog
  0.1.1 (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.139).  xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.139 fixes
  `bgp-params / no default-ipv4-unicast` being silently dropped — the
  XCESP schema, mapper and FRR fragment writer all defaulted to
  false-and-only-emit-on-true, but FRR's default for `bgp default
  ipv4-unicast` is enabled, so writing `no default-ipv4-unicast`
  produced no FRR command at all.  EVPN-only setups that rely on
  disabling the IPv4 unicast AF now work correctly

## 0.1.36

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.10, xcespcli 0.1.9, xcespproc 0.1.14, xcespwdog
  0.1.1 (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.138).  xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.138 makes
  `RtrMplsLdpPObj`'s MPLS sysctl writes (per-ns `platform_labels`,
  per-iface `input=1`) retryable on every `process()` cycle until they
  all stick.  Symptom from the Debian smoke test: one LDP-enabled
  interface had `input=1`, another had `input=0` because that interface
  hadn't been created yet when `applyConfig` ran the first time

## 0.1.35

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.10, xcespcli 0.1.9, xcespproc 0.1.13, xcespwdog
  0.1.1 (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.137).  xcespcli 0.1.9: `dump-file` resolves
  relative filenames against `<DSK_DIR>/cap/` so tcpdump can actually
  write — bare `dump-file ... file ldp.pcap` was failing on both Debian
  and ARM64 with `tcpdump: ldp.pcap: Permission denied` because
  xcespproc's cwd is not writable by the unprivileged `xcesp` user

## 0.1.34

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.10, xcespcli 0.1.8, xcespproc 0.1.13, xcespwdog
  0.1.1 (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.137).  xcespserver 0.1.10 detects strongSwan
  6.x's `/usr/sbin/charon-systemd` so `show server` correctly reports
  `strongswan: enabled (...)` on Debian 13 hosts that ship only the
  systemd-aware charon variant

## 0.1.33

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.9, xcespcli 0.1.8, xcespproc 0.1.13, xcespwdog
  0.1.1 (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.137).  Completes the MPLS data-plane fix:
  0.1.32 added the per-interface `input=1` write in `RtrMplsLdpPObj`,
  but `RtrInterfacePObj` was still unconditionally writing
  `net.mpls.conf.<dev>.input=0` on every iteration — silently
  clobbering the LDP write so the wire kept dropping labelled packets.
  0.0.137 makes the `input=0` write conditional on having previously
  enabled MPLS through the interface schema, so the two writers
  coexist.  After installing 0.1.33, `sudo ip netns exec RA sysctl
  net.mpls.conf.<rlink>.input` should report `1` for every
  LDP-enabled interface, and the failover ping over the LSP should
  succeed

## 0.1.32

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.9, xcespcli 0.1.8, xcespproc 0.1.12, xcespwdog
  0.1.1 (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.136).  xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.136 enables the kernel
  MPLS data plane when an `mpls-ldp` block is present:
  `net.mpls.platform_labels` per namespace and
  `net.mpls.conf.<iface>.input` per LDP-enabled interface.  Without these
  ldpd was distributing labels but the kernel was silently dropping
  every labelled packet — the Debian three-router smoke test showed
  100% loss after taking RA-RB down even though the wire carried
  correctly-labelled MPLS frames

## 0.1.31

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.9, xcespcli 0.1.8, xcespproc 0.1.11, xcespwdog
  0.1.1 (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.135).  xcespcli 0.1.8 reworks the
  `show mpls-ldp ipv4-interfaces` table: drops the unused `Transport`
  column (FRR's per-interface JSON has no transport-address field) and
  adds `State`, `Uptime`, `Hello-Hold`, `AdjCount`.  New layout:
  Interface | AF | State | Uptime | Hello-Int | Hello-Hold | AdjCount

## 0.1.30

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.9, xcespcli 0.1.7, xcespproc 0.1.11, xcespwdog
  0.1.1 (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.135).  xcespcli 0.1.7 fixes the MPLS LDP
  show-formatters that surfaced after the OSPF push fix unblocked the
  Debian smoke test:
  - `show mpls-ldp ipv4-interfaces` was always empty.  FRR's
    `show mpls ldp <af> interface json` returns an object keyed by
    `"<ifname>: <af>"`, not the array the formatter assumed.
    `ldpExtractArray()` now also flattens object-of-objects
  - `show mpls-ldp ipv4-bindings` rendered `*` in the Neighbor column.
    FRR uses `neighborId` for the next-hop IP; the formatter only looked
    for `neighbor`/`peer`/`lsrId`.  Added an `In-Use` column derived
    from FRR's 0/1 `inUse` integer; reordered columns to match FRR's
    text output: Prefix | Neighbor | Local-Label | Remote-Label | In-Use

## 0.1.29

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.9, xcespcli 0.1.6, xcespproc 0.1.11, xcespwdog 0.1.1
  (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.135) with two fixes uncovered while smoke-testing OSPF
  on a Debian box that has FRR built with `--enable-ldpd`:
  - **OSPF push loop**: `RtrOspfPObj::loadConfig()` now strips the `-`
    placeholder that the mapper emits for empty optional ospf-interface
    fields (`network-type`, `auth-mode`, `md5-key`).  An ospf-interface
    with `passive` but no `network-type` was making FRR reject the entire
    fragment with `% Unknown command[21]: ip ospf network -` and the push
    retried in a loop
  - **`show <protocol>` token expansion + autocompletion**: xcespcli now
    has explicit completion entries for `show {ospf|ospf6|rip|ripng|bfd|
    mpls-ldp}`.  Without them, `expandTokens()` rewrote unique-prefix
    tokens via `validNavWords()` — so `show ospf route router RA` typed
    at the root path was being expanded to `show ospf router router RA`
    and rejected with `usage: ...`

## 0.1.28

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.9, xcespcli 0.1.5, xcespproc 0.1.10, xcespwdog 0.1.1
  (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.134) with: MPLS LDP support (`mpls-ldp` config block,
  `RtrMplsLdp` proc-object, `show mpls-ldp …`), L3-EVPN IP-VRF advertising
  (`advertise-evpn` block, VRF VNI binding), `clear-ndp` action, FRR ldpd
  daemon-availability detection (`show server` → `frr/ldpd` row), and a
  `RtrFrrPObj::writeDaemonsFile()` fix that appends `<daemon>=yes` when the
  distro `daemons` template lacks the line (Fedora omits `ldpd=`/`babeld=`)

## 0.1.27

- `install.sh`: never call package managers automatically.  v0.1.26 ran `dnf install kernel-modules-extra` when modules were missing, which is intrusive and breaks on isolated VMs without repository access (dnf hangs on the network timeout).  Now we just warn the user, list the missing modules, and provide the exact command to install them — leaving the decision to the user
- Same xcespserver 0.1.8 / xcespproc 0.1.9 binaries as v0.1.26

## 0.1.26

- `install.sh`: detect when required kernel modules are missing from disk and auto-install `kernel-modules-extra-$(uname -r)` via dnf when available.  On Fedora, `l2tp_netlink` and `l2tp_eth` (and some mpls/vxlan variants) ship in the optional `kernel-modules-extra` RPM, not the default `kernel-modules` — minimal Fedora cloud images / VMs fail `ip l2tp add tunnel` with "Error talking to the kernel" because the L2TP genetlink family is registered by `l2tp_netlink`, which simply isn't present
- ARM64 builds with `CONFIG_L2TP_*=y` (built-in to vmlinuz) were unaffected
- Same xcespserver 0.1.8, xcespproc 0.1.9 binaries as 0.1.25

## 0.1.25

- `install.sh`: pre-load all kernel modules (mpls, l2tp, vxlan) directly during install — install.sh runs as root so this bypasses any sudoers/capability propagation issues.  Modules stay resident until reboot or rmmod, so xcespproc / xcespserver inherit a known-good state regardless of how they later call modprobe
- `install.sh`: restart `xcesp.service` after upgrade if it is currently running, so the user immediately runs the new binaries (previous releases required a manual `systemctl restart xcesp` step that some users missed — explaining the v0.1.23/v0.1.24 reports of L2TP still failing after upgrade)
- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.8 and xcespproc 0.1.9 (unchanged from v0.1.24)

## 0.1.24

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.8 (with the corrected `loadConfiguredModules` logic)
- Fixes the v0.1.23 regression: xcespserver was supposed to pre-load the full L2TP module set, but `loadConfiguredModules` had an early-skip when the primary module (`l2tp_core`) was already loaded — which is the default state on Fedora — so siblings (`l2tp_netlink`, `l2tp_ip`, `l2tp_eth`) were never loaded.  v0.1.8 now modprobes every module unconditionally
- ARM64 unaffected (modules built-in)

## 0.1.23

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.7, xcespproc 0.1.9 (with xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.133)
- **L2TP module loading fix for Fedora VMs**: Fedora kernels ship `l2tp_*` as separate `.ko` files and only `l2tp_core` is loaded by default; the L2TP genetlink family (registered by `l2tp_netlink`) was missing, so `ip l2tp add tunnel` failed with "Error talking to the kernel" / RTNETLINK ENOENT.  Now both layers load the full set:
  - xcespserver pre-loads `l2tp_core`, `l2tp_netlink`, `l2tp_ip`, `l2tp_eth` at startup via sudo when `l2tp true` is configured
  - xcespproc's `applyL2tp()` also modprobes `l2tp_netlink` directly
- `install.sh`: add `cap_sys_module` to xcespproc file capabilities (so xcespproc can load modules without sudo, consistent with xcesptest's `activate.sh`)
- `install.sh`: extend the `xcesp-modprobe` sudoers rule to allow `modprobe l2tp_netlink`, `l2tp_ip`, `l2tp_eth` (was only `l2tp_core` before)
- ARM64 builds with `CONFIG_L2TP_*=y` (built-in) were unaffected by the original bug

## 0.1.22

- Bundles xcespproc 0.1.8 (with xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.132)
- xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.132: amended L2TP-in-VRF support for L2TP IP encap pseudowires.  Adds `<local>/32` to `lo` so the kernel's `l2tp_ip_bind()` finds the address in the main local table; leaks `<remote>/32` into the main routing table via the rlink slave; sets `raw_l3mdev_accept=1` so the receive socket accepts packets arriving on VRF slave interfaces.  Works under SELinux on Fedora (where `ip vrf exec` is blocked) and on VM/ARM64 deployments
- xcespserver, xcespcli, xcespwdog: unchanged

## 0.1.21

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.6, xcespcli 0.1.4, xcespproc 0.1.7 (with xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.130)
- xcespproc 0.1.7: IPsec spoke retry — xcespproc explicitly re-initiates `start_action=start` connections every `retry-interval` seconds after NO_PROPOSAL_CHOSEN; fixes mGRE hub/spoke race where spokes initiate before hub loads its config
- xcespproc 0.1.7: namespace socket directory created via `::mkdir()` fallback — no longer silently fails when sudo NOPASSWD rule for mkdir is absent
- xcespserver 0.1.6: extended strongSwan binary detection — covers RHEL/Debian ARM64 charon and swanctl paths
- xcespcli 0.1.4: prompt path truncation for deep config nesting

## 0.1.14

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.5: logo banner now shows xcesppkg version (read from `mainsw/VERSION`) instead of xcespserver build version
- `install.sh`: create `/home/xcesp` (mode 0750) and `/home/xcesp/.ssh` (mode 0700) after user creation — xcesp user was created without a home directory, causing scp/sftp to fail with "Could not create directory '/home/xcesp/.ssh'"
- `scripts/xcesp-activate`: also create `/home/xcesp` and `/home/xcesp/.ssh` on every service start to fix existing installs without requiring reinstall

## 0.1.13

- Bundles xcespproc 0.1.6 (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.125): NAT namespace entry now uses direct `setns()` instead of `ip netns exec` — fixes `Permission denied` when the `ip` binary has file capabilities that stripped `CAP_NET_ADMIN` from `iptables-legacy` on embedded ARM64

## 0.1.12

- `scripts/xcesp-activate`: create `/run/xtables.lock` with `root:xcesp 0664` permissions on every service start — `iptables-legacy` requires this file to exist and be group-writable; on embedded systems `/run` is tmpfs and the file is absent after boot, causing `Permission denied` even when xcespproc has `cap_net_admin`

## 0.1.11

- Bundles xcespproc 0.1.5 (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.124): auto-detect `iptables-legacy` and use it over `iptables-nft` for DNAT/SNAT rules; fixes `unknown option "--to-destination"` on embedded ARM64 systems where iptables is the nf_tables variant

## 0.1.10

- Bundles xcespproc 0.1.4 (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.123): NAT iptables failures now visible as WARNING; `modprobe -a nf_conntrack iptable_nat` added before every DNAT/SNAT apply to fix NAT rules not applied on embedded ARM64 kernels; `CAP_NET_RAW` ambient capability propagation corrected

## 0.1.9

- `scripts/xcesp-activate`: add `cap_net_raw` to xcespproc `setcap` call — was missing from xcesp-activate (though present in install.sh since 0.1.4), causing every `systemctl restart xcesp` to strip `cap_net_raw` back off xcespproc and break ping inside network namespaces

## 0.1.8

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.4, xcespcli 0.1.3 with xcespproc 0.1.3, xcespwdog (unchanged)
- `scripts/xcesp-activate`: fix awk parser for `processes routing / count N` — use anchored patterns to distinguish indented child-block `!` from the unindented server-block `!`; a `license-code` block's closing `!` previously reset `in_server` before reaching the `processes` section, silently reverting to the default of 2 routing processes
- `scripts/xcesp-activate`: add router-count fallback — when no explicit `processes routing` block exists, counts `^router ` lines in `xcespserver.conf` as the routing process count

## 0.1.7

- `install.sh`: add `Defaults:xcesp !use_pty` to xcesp-frr sudoers file — systems with global `Defaults use_pty` block sudo in service processes that have no TTY
- `install.sh`: append `@includedir /etc/sudoers.d` to `/etc/sudoers` when the includedir line is missing — embedded systems often ship without it, making all drop-in sudoers rules invisible

## 0.1.6

- Bundles xcespproc 0.1.3 (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.122): FRR startup no longer uses `sudo -n` when running as root; timeout error shows log first line and exact sudoers fix command

## 0.1.5

- Bundles xcespproc 0.1.2 (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.121): FRR startup failures now logged to `/tmp/frr_<ns>.log` with 30 s timeout error

## 0.1.4

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.3, xcespcli 0.1.2
- `install.sh`: add `cap_net_raw` to xcespproc capabilities — required for ping inside network namespaces; previously missing (xcesptest/activate.sh had it, install.sh did not)

## 0.1.3

- `install.sh`: fix venv detection — check `import ensurepip` instead of
  `import venv`; on Debian/Ubuntu `venv` is importable even without the
  `python3-venv` package, but `ensurepip` is the module that package actually
  provides and that `python3 -m venv` requires to succeed

## 0.1.2

- `install.sh`: make Python venv optional — if `python3-venv` is not available,
  xcesppy source is copied to `/var/xcesp/lib/python/` and registered via a
  `.pth` file in the system's `site-packages` directory; venv is still used
  when available as the cleaner isolation option

